{"title": "Functional Addict", "content": "Because Drugs Are Bad, the world of fiction is famous for treating drug addicts as feeble, broken people living in disheveled apartments (or in a worst case scenario, homeless) and constantly muttering to themselves. However, there has been a general trend lately towards portraying addicts in a more positive light. These drug users, with addictions just as serious, can lead very normal lives, at least to the strangers on the street. They can wake up in the morning, go to work, have a family, and interact socially without any noticeable problems, as long as they are getting their \"fix\" when necessary.\n\nSimply put, the addiction does not rule this person's life. Typically, this kind of addict can go long periods of time without getting their \"medicine\" and doesn't depend on their drugs as a \"crutch\". Often, this is because they can always get the drug when they need it or have the willpower to keep themselves from getting out of control.\n\nIn Real Life these kinds of addicts can go their entire lives without ever becoming dysfunctional. It isn't real likely, but it can happen. Fiction, on the other hand, almost always treats them as ticking time-bombs, slowly working up to the one event that will send them over the edge. While crossing the line into dysfunctional territory definitely happens in Real Life as well, the key difference is that fictional sources treat this as inevitable.\n\nCould be justified because fiction typically involves putting characters through unusual, dramatic, and stressful situations which does increase the likelihood of an addict becoming dysfunctional. Also, conservation of detail comes into play. It's usually not worth mentioning that the character has an addiction if it plays no role in the plot and tells us nothing important about the character.\n\nIt's common for none of the other characters in the work to even know that there is an issue until it becomes a severe problem. It is also commonly used as The Reveal for a particular character on a Very Special Episode, where it is revealed they have been a functional addict throughout the series and are now coming to terms with it.\n\nCompare Dark Secret, for characters with any kind of sinister secret in hiding, and Drugs Are Bad, for when problematic drug use is the only kind of drug use. Also compare/contrast Addled Addict, when drugs are taking their toll. Compare Recovered Addict, who may cycle into and out of addiction.", "url": "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/FunctionalAddict", "media_links": ["/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/Leverage", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/MaidenRose", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/NeonGenesisEvangelion", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/ACruelGodReigns", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/CopernicusBreathing", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/PrivateActress", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/MissKobayashisDragonMaid", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/Cruelty", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/TransformersMoreThanMeetsTheEye", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/BlueIsTheWarmestColor", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/StarWarsLegacy", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/Revival", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/TheGoldenAge", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/Chassis", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/BakerStreet", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WesternAnimation/Incredibles2", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/CarlitosWay", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TheExpendables", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/DieHard", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/GhostsOfMars", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/NatashaHenstridge", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/JasonStatham", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/MinorityReport", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/PitchBlack", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/RequiemForADream", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TropicThunder", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/ChrisFarley", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/BadLieutenantPortOfCallNewOrleans", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/WintersBone", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/ForAFewDollarsMore", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TheWorldsEnd", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/LifeO